It cannot really be the case that a Delaware court can stop any Delaware co=
rporation from moving its state of incorporation to Texas. But it might=C2=
=A0be the case that a Delaware court could stop=C2=A0Tesla=C2=A0from moving=
 to Texas.
Today  the Wall Street Journal has a story previewing this news:

Three powerful shareholders are trying to loosen Delaware=E2=80=99s long-he=
ld grip over public companies.=C2=A0
Tripadvisor, under media executive Greg Maffei, wants to reincorporate in N=
evada, over the objection of minority shareholders. Billionaire Barry Dille=
r is awaiting a ruling that could relax Delaware=E2=80=99s scrutiny of tran=
sactions like the 2020 split of some of his online businesses. And Elon Mus=
k, who reincorporated Twitter as X in Nevada last year, has said he would a=
sk shareholders about reincorporating Tesla in Texas.

The stuff about Musk and Tesla and Texas, sure. But I want to focus on Trip=
Advisor, because that is the real preview of what could happen with Tesla. =
TripAdvisor Inc.,=C2=A0and its parent company, Liberty Tripadvisor Holdings=
 Inc., are Delaware public=C2=A0companies that are run and controlled by Gr=
eg Maffei, who has supervoting stock and does, uh, fun stuff with his votin=
g power. He gets sued by shareholders sometimes, and apparently wanted to r=
eincorporate his companies to Nevada to get sued less: Nevada=E2=80=99s cor=
porate law seems to be friendlier to corporate officers and controlling sha=
reholders, with =E2=80=9Cbroad protections for directors and officers in ma=
ny cases that Delaware wouldn=E2=80=99t, including involving improper perso=
nal gain,=E2=80=9D according to the Journal.
And the companies=E2=80=99 boards of directors considered moving to Nevada,=
 and the directors decided it was a good idea, and they=C2=A0asked sharehol=
ders to vote to approve the move, and the shareholders approved. Well, Maff=
ei=C2=A0approved, and he has supervoting shares; a majority of the independ=
ent shareholders voted against the proposals to move, but they passed anywa=
y.=C2=A0
But some shareholders sued to stop=C2=A0Maffei from doing=C2=A0this. Here i=
s  their complaint.
  [1]
=C2=A0The argument is essentially:
=09Under Delaware corporate law, a company=E2=80=99s board of directors and=
 controlling shareholder have fiduciary duties to the ordinary=C2=A0shareho=
lders, and they can=E2=80=99t do something =E2=80=94=C2=A0even something ot=
herwise legal, like reincorporating to Nevada =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it violates=
 their fiduciary duties.=09Where the board and controlling shareholder have=
 a conflict of interest =E2=80=94=C2=A0where they get something from a tran=
saction at the expense of ordinary shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0then Delawar=
e will review the transaction for =E2=80=9Centire fairness=E2=80=9D: The tr=
ansaction is a breach of fiduciary duties, and so not allowed, unless the c=
ourt finds that it is =E2=80=9Centirely fair=E2=80=9D to the ordinary share=
holders.=09Maffei and his board of directors get something out of moving to=
 Nevada (they get to not be sued for doing creative stuff with their contro=
l of the companies), and this comes at the expense of the ordinary sharehol=
ders (they don't get to sue if Maffei does creative stuff to them).
  [2]

=09But the ordinary shareholders were not compensated for this, and voted a=
gainst it, and the board did not have a special committee of independent di=
rectors to consider the move: It just did what Maffei wanted. So=C2=A0the m=
ove is surely not =E2=80=9Centirely fair=E2=80=9D to them.=09So a Delaware =
court can and should stop TripAdvisor and Liberty TripAdvisor from moving t=
o Nevada, so that Delaware can continue to keep an eye on Maffei for the be=
nefit of the ordinary shareholders.

And that kind of=C2=A0is=C2=A0how Delaware law works. In fact, this is more=
 or less the same reasoning that a Delaware court applied last month to   s=
trike down Musk=E2=80=99s pay package:
=09Tesla=E2=80=99s directors =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Musk, who the court found i=
s the =E2=80=9Ccontrolling shareholder=E2=80=9D of Tesla even though he doe=
sn=E2=80=99t own supervoting shares or a majority of the stock =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0have fiduciary duties to Tesla=E2=80=99s ordinary shareholders.=09Confli=
cted transactions need to be entirely fair to those shareholders.=09Musk go=
t something out of his pay package (options worth more than $55 billion),=
=C2=A0at the expense of ordinary shareholders (who got diluted).=09The ordi=
nary shareholders=C2=A0did=C2=A0actually vote to approve the pay package, b=
ut the judge found that their vote was not fully informed.=09And the judge =
found that the pay package wasn=E2=80=99t entirely fair to shareholders =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0basically, Musk wasn=E2=80=99t worth what he was paid =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0so she blocked it.

And Maffei doesn=E2=80=99t really argue against this framework. Instead, hi=
s lawyers argue that there is no conflict of interest here, because Maffei =
and the directors want to move to Nevada for good corporate governance reas=
ons, and they aren=E2=80=99t getting any personal benefits. From their  mot=
ion to dismiss:

Plaintiffs ask this Court to do something that has never been done before =
=E2=80=94 prevent a corporation from leaving the state of Delaware notwiths=
tanding its undisputed compliance with the provisions of the [Delaware Gene=
ral Corporation Law]=C2=A0that allow the corporation to do so.
Section 266 of the DGCL gives corporations the right to leave Delaware and =
reorganize under the laws of another jurisdiction. Plaintiffs seek to limit=
