gue that where, as here, a corporation decides to move from Delaware to a s=
tate that potentially provides officers and directors with greater protecti=
on from future litigation based on conduct that has not yet occurred =E2=80=
=94 and thus claims that do not yet exist=E2=80=94the Court should enjoin t=
he move as a breach of the directors=E2=80=99 (and, in this case, an allege=
d controller=E2=80=99s) fiduciary duty.=C2=A0

Because there=E2=80=99s no conflict, Maffei argues, the Delaware court shou=
ld defer to the board=E2=80=99s business judgment rather than conduct its o=
wn review of the fairness of moving to Nevada:

Plaintiffs theorize that the Directors were conflicted because there might =
be future board decisions that might give rise to litigation claims and suc=
h claims might survive a motion to dismiss in Delaware, but not in Nevada. =
As explained below, Plaintiffs=E2=80=99 speculation is too hypothetical and=
 remote to constitute a unique benefit today. The Amended Complaint does no=
t allege any existing or even inchoate litigation claim that the Conversion=
s would extinguish. Plaintiffs=E2=80=99 hypothesized conflict arises from t=
he mere possibility that the Boards might take some unidentified action in =
the future=E2=80=94after the Companies have moved to Nevada =E2=80=94 that =
could give rise to a future stockholder claim. But the risk of a future unk=
nown stockholder claim is one every board faces and is not sufficient to re=
quire entire fairness review, much less prevent a corporation from electing=
 to move to another state. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0
The Amended Complaint does not contain factual allegations supporting a rea=
sonably conceivable inference that the Directors or Maffei have a financial=
 interest in the transaction or that Maffei would obtain some unique benefi=
t from the Conversions.

And that=E2=80=99s reasonable. But later this year, when we talk about Elon=
 Musk moving Tesla to Texas, he won=E2=80=99t be able to make that argument=
. He will have a=C2=A0very very clear financial interest=C2=A0in the transa=
ction: A Delaware court just struck down his $55 billion pay package, and e=
ven before that he was  going around posting that he wanted another enormou=
s stock grant so that he can control at least 25% of Tesla=E2=80=99s stock.=
 And if he can=E2=80=99t get it in Delaware, he=E2=80=99ll go to Texas.
I am sure that, when Tesla actually asks its shareholders to approve reinco=
rporating in Texas, it will have good lawyers write=C2=A0a proxy statement =
emphasizing the many corporate benefits of Texas, the importance of attract=
ing and retaining talent=C2=A0and the value that Musk provides to Tesla. I =
don=E2=80=99t even think that will be wrong; I think there is something odd=
, and perhaps shareholder-unfriendly, about a Delaware judge striking down =
a pay package that Tesla=E2=80=99s board=C2=A0and shareholders=C2=A0thought=
 was a good idea. I just think that Elon Musk is not the most carefully law=
yered guy in the world in his personal statements, and he will have made =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0he has already made =E2=80=94=C2=A0a very clear record provi=
ng that he wants to move to Texas=C2=A0so that he can make Tesla give him $=
75 billion worth of stock.
  [3]

So shareholders will go to the Delaware=C2=A0judge saying =E2=80=9CElon Mus=
k tried to pay himself $55 billion, and you stopped him from doing that bec=
ause it was unfair to shareholders, and now he is trying to move Tesla to T=
exas so that he can (1) get rid of you and (2) pay himself=C2=A0$75 billion=
, so you have to stop him again.=E2=80=9D And I think that is an argument t=
hat the Delaware judge might find compelling? I mean, she=C2=A0did=C2=A0sto=
p Musk from paying himself $55 billion. Presumably this move will be even m=
ore offensive.
And Tesla=C2=A0is=C2=A0a Delaware corporation, so it=C2=A0is=C2=A0subject t=
o the orders of the=C2=A0Delaware court, even if those orders are =E2=80=9C=
where do you think you=E2=80=99re going? Get back here you little scamp!=E2=
=80=9D And so maybe Tesla really can=E2=80=99t leave?
Anyway, that=E2=80=99s the news from six months from now, and I suppose whe=
n it actually happens I will just write some comical imagined dialogue for =
Musk and say =E2=80=9Csee previous column.=E2=80=9D There are some risks to=
 this thesis:
=09Musk could appeal=C2=A0the decision about his compensation and win, and =
then he might lose interest in moving to Texas.=C2=A0I kind of think that h=
e=E2=80=99ll want to move even if he wins on appeal, though.=09Maffei could=
 win such a comprehensive victory in the TripAdvisor case that nobody will =
even be able to argue that a court can stop Musk from leaving Delaware, so =
Tesla will=C2=A0just leave with no problem.=09Maffei could=C2=A0lose=C2=A0s=
o comprehensively that Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers will tell him =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=
=80=99ve got no shot at leaving Delaware, don=E2=80=99t even bother,=E2=80=
=9D and he=E2=80=99ll believe them and give that up. I assign 0% probabilit=
y to this one.=09Moving to Texas might be a thing that Musk posts about but=
 does not actually plan to do?

I don=E2=80=99t know; I think it=E2=80=99s gonna happen. Last week  Musk mo=
