<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Multistrategy</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/34321970.285393/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMDgvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudHMteW91ci1tb25leT9jbXBpZD1CQ=
kQwMjEyMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRl=
ciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBd7879b3c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  wrote the other day</a> that Bill Ackman=E2=80=99=
s hedge fund, Pershing Square LP, =E2=80=9Cis kind of what you think of whe=
n you think of a hedge fund.=E2=80=9D But then I realized (in a footnote) t=
hat I needed to qualify that statement. I don=E2=80=99t know what you think=
 of when you think of a hedge fund. I think there are two main models. Ther=
e is what I think of as the old-school classic hedge fund,=C2=A0like Pershi=
ng Square, where one high-profile manager makes a handful of concentrated h=
igh-conviction market bets using his natural talent and hard work and marke=
t experience and=C2=A0gut instinct.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then there is the newer model of multimana=
ger, multistrategy hedge funds, or =E2=80=9Cpod shops,=E2=80=9D like Citade=
l or Millennium or Point72, that have a bunch of different portfolio=C2=A0m=
anagers each making bets in some particular sector or strategy. Unlike the =
old-school managers, the pod-shop portfolio managers don=E2=80=99t usually =
go on television that much.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also unlike the classic funds, <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34321970.285393/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud=
GhlZGlmZi5jby9hcmNoaXZlL3BvZC1wZW9wbGUv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8511bfda" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> the pod shops are run</a> on, as it were, scientific lines. I mean=
, the portfolio managers might trade on gut instinct, but they are=C2=A0<em=
>managed=C2=A0</em>scientifically.=C2=A0Each portfolio manager will general=
ly be tasked with producing returns that are not correlated with the broade=
r market or the sector she invests in: The consumer discretionary manager w=
on=E2=80=99t get a bonus just because consumer discretionary stocks do well=
; she=E2=80=99ll only get paid if she buys the best consumer discretionary =
stocks and shorts the worst ones. She will be required to be more or less f=
actor-neutral, to run a portfolio that makes money on the strength of her i=
deas rather than on broad market trends. And her bosses will have <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34321970.285393/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9BZHZhbmNlZC1Qb3J0Zm9saW8tTWFuYWdlbWVudC1GdW5kYW1lbnRh=
bC1JbnZlc3RvcnMvZHAvMTExOTc4OTc5Ng/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9ee6ac7c" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> quite sophisticated techniques</a> to measure her performance and her s=
kill, to neutralize standard market factors and to extract only alpha, only=
 the returns to skilled investing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The appeal of the multimanager funds, to insti=
tutional investors, is obvious: They can offer=C2=A0<em>true alpha</em>, tr=
ue uncorrelated returns. They can tell allocators: =E2=80=9COkay, you can g=
et your stock-market exposure from stock index funds, your bond-market expo=
sure from bonds, your real estate exposure from buying real estate, whateve=
r, and then you can diversify your portfolio by putting some money into our=
 fund and we=E2=80=99ll just pay you 12% per year with very little volatili=
ty.=E2=80=9D This is not a pitch that appeals to everyone: Plenty of people=
 want the charismatic gut-instinct-driven single manager who might put all =
her money on=C2=A0one big bet that returns 300%. But it is a pitch that app=
eals to sober, sensible institutional asset allocators with a lot of money.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(Incidentally, one model of why Ackman is laun=
ching a public closed-end fund designed to appeal to US retail investors no=
w is precisely that institutional investors increasingly want the scientifi=
c multimanager model, and the classic charismatic-manager model is maybe a =
bit outdated. But it=E2=80=99s still popular with retail investors on Twitt=
er/X!)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is, however, a downside for investors fr=
om all of this scientific management. The downside is that the multimanager=
 funds might get=C2=A0<em>too good=C2=A0</em>at scientifically analyzing pe=
rformance, and at attributing it to skill. The fund manager might be able t=
o say something like =E2=80=9Cokay this portfolio returned $47 million last=
 year, of which $13=C2=A0million is attributable to the analysts=E2=80=99 r=
esearch, $14 million to the portfolio manager=E2=80=99s stock-picking, $11 =
million to our firm=E2=80=99s risk management and $9 million to our investo=
rs=E2=80=99 capital.=E2=80=9D And then the investors get the $9 million and=
 the fund manager and analysts and portfolio manager get the rest. If you g=
et too good at measuring the returns to investment skill, you might, uh, pa=
y all of those returns to the people whose skill generated them? And what d=
oes that leave for investors?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34321970.285393/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
