er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  Nishant Kumar and Liza Tetley report</a>:</=
p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The priciest multistrategy hedge funds are now=
 keeping most of the profits they generate, while clients shoulder their co=
sts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Clients received 41 cents of every $1 made by =
multistrategy funds that passed on all their costs last year, according to =
a survey by the prime brokerage unit of BNP Paribas SA. Their share is down=
 from 54 cents in 2021, reflecting a startling new reality where the most p=
opular funds effectively have a blank check for expenses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These funds outperformed peers, and most of th=
e wider industry, on investment returns. However, gains measured after fees=
 are the lowest among multistrategy funds, the poll of 238 allocators manag=
ing or advising on $1.2 trillion in hedge fund assets found.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, right, in the olden days a charismatic ma=
nager would take big swings on a handful of stocks and=C2=A0would make a lo=
t of money. Nobody would be sure =E2=80=94=C2=A0or would even=C2=A0<em>ask=
=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0how much of the returns were due to the manager=
=E2=80=99s skill and how much were just, like, the stock market went up. Bu=
t the crude compromise would be that the manager paid herself 2% of assets =
and 20% of profits and the investors got the rest. In modern multimanager f=
unds, the fund can say =E2=80=9Cwell 59% of this performance is clearly att=
ributable to our skill so we=E2=80=99re keeping it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile it=E2=80=99s not all great for the p=
ortfolio managers either. At Business Insider, <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34321970.285393/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3Npbn=
NpZGVyLmNvbS9ub3JpYXMtcmVzZWFyY2gtbGF1bmNoLXN0cmF0ZWd5LWZlZXMtMjAyNC0y/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdae71234" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bradley Sacks reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Former Point72 president=C2=A0Doug=C2=A0Haynes=
=C2=A0is looking to revive a strategy he previously ran for billionaire Ste=
ve Cohen for his new fund launch.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The quantamental strategy =E2=80=94 which blen=
ds fundamental stockpicking and algorithm-based number crunching =E2=80=94 =
was internally known at Point72 as Idea Lab while under=C2=A0Haynes=C2=A0an=
d then eventually became Latitude before shuttering in 2020. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It's an alpha capture-type strategy in which 1=
2 West Palm Beach-based analysts will come up with investment ideas, and a =
systematic algorithm will create a portfolio based on the ideas and analyti=
cal tools that focus on position sizing and risk management. The firm =E2=
=80=94 which hopes to raise $1 billion =E2=80=94 has "substantial investor =
interest," according to a spokesman for the firm, and is set to launch on A=
pril 1.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If your scientific management determines that =
the analysts add most of the value and that the portfolio managers can just=
 be automated away, that=E2=80=99s what you do.</p>
